.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
utility initializes and edits documents, ideal for building an indexed list of notes documents.
.Pp
By default, the file extension for each new document is the extension of the last numbered document in the folder.
If the folder has no numbered documents,
.Nm
defaults to
.Pa .md .
If the folder has a template file
.Ql nt_template. Ns Ar extension ,
then each new document uses this template's content and
.Ar extension .
The template supports the following macros:
.Cm %DATE
is replaced with today's date (yyyy-mm-dd), and
.Cm %TITLE
is replaced with the title passed to
.Cm new .
.Pp
If
.Nm
is given a
.Ar title
when creating or renaming a doc, the delimiter (underscores or hyphens) between the numeric index and the title portion of the file name will match the format of the last doc, defaulting to a single hyphen.
.Pp
As syntactic sugar, you can pass in multiple numeric indices, as well as
.Cm R
and/or
.Cm t
in a row to open the specified files all at once.
.Pp
Title-consuming commands
.Pq Cm n , Cm r , Cm rl
accept an optional hyphen prefix
.Pq e.g., Fl n , Fl r .
Without a hyphen, the command treats all remaining words as the title.
With a hyphen, it stops at the first hyphen-prefixed flag, so you can chain
multiple commands on one line.
Chained commands are processed in the sequence they are passed:
.Pp
.Dl nt -n my note -3 -r 7 new-title -R
.Pp
creates a note titled
.Dq my note ,
then opens doc 3, renames doc 7, and opens the README \(em all in one go.
.Pp
Options include:
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Bro Cm h | Cm help Brc
Print help page.
.It Bro Cm n | Cm new Brc Op Cm i Ar index Op Cm c Ar index Op Ar title
Create a new document named with the highest unused numeric index (0-padded to 3 digits)
followed by a delimiter and a hyphenated version of the
.Ar title ,
with the same extension as the previous document (or .md), then open it in the preferred editor.
If the current directory contains the file
.Ql nt_template. Ns Ar extension ,
then the new document uses this template's content and
.Ar extension
instead.
.Pp
If
.Cm i
(or
.Cm index )
is given, use
.Ar index
instead of auto-incrementing.
All index components are zero-padded to 3 digits.
Fails if a document with that index already exists.
.Pp
If
.Cm c
(or
.Cm copy )
is given, copy the content verbatim from the document at the specified
.Ar index .
The extension is inherited from the source document.
When both
.Cm i
and
.Cm c
are given, they may appear in any order.
.It Bro Cm l | Cm last Brc Op Ar N
Open the document with the latest numeric index.
If
.Ar N
is a positive integer, open the
.Ar N Ns th-to-last
indexed document (1 = last, 2 = second-to-last, etc.).
When using the hyphen-prefixed form, a leading-hyphen next argument is passed on to the next chained command rather than treated as an argument to
.Cm l .
.It Bro Cm li | Cm last-index Brc
Print the numeric index of the last indexed document in the current directory.
.It Ar num Op Ar ...
Open the existing document(s) with the
.Ar num
index (indices).
.It Ar num Ns Cm - Ns Ar num
Open all documents whose index falls between the two endpoints, inclusive.
Both endpoints may be hierarchical (e.g.,
.Ql 1.3-1.7
or
.Ql 3-5.2 ) .
Documents at any depth within the range are included.
Missing indices are silently skipped.
Fails if no documents exist in the range or if the start is greater than the end.
.It Ar num Ns Cm \&..
Open all descendants under
.Ar num
(direct and indirect sub-indices), excluding
.Ar num
itself.
For example,
.Ql 1..
opens
.Pa 001.001-a.md , 001.002-b.md , 001.002.001-deep.md ,
etc.
.It Ar num Ns Cm \&.
Open only the immediate children of
.Ar num
(one level deeper), excluding
.Ar num
itself and any deeper descendants.
For example,
.Ql 1.
opens
.Pa 001.001-a.md , 001.002-b.md
but not
.Pa 001.002.001-deep.md .
.It Bro Cm r | Cm rename Brc Ar num Ar title
Rename the existing document with the
.Ar num
index to
.Ar title
without opening the document.
.It Cm rl Ar title
Rename the last indexed document to
.Ar title
without opening the document.
.It Bro Cm ri | Cm reindex Brc Ar n Ar m
Reindex the document at index
.Ar n
to use index
.Ar m
instead, preserving the delimiter, title, and extension.
The index depth may change
.Pq e.g., moving Pa 003-note.md to index Ar 1.5 .
Fails if no document exists at
.Ar n
or if
.Ar m
is already occupied.
.It Bro Cm ri | Cm reindex Brc Ar n Ns Cm - Ns Ar m Ar a Ns Cm - Ns Ar b
Reindex the documents in the source range
.Ar n Ns - Ns Ar m
to the target range
.Ar a Ns - Ns Ar b
one-to-one:
.Ar n Ns -> Ns Ar a ,
.Ar n Ns +1 Ns -> Ns Ar a Ns +1 ,
and so on.
Both range endpoints must be at the same index depth and share the same parent index
.Pq e.g., Ql 3.3-3.7 No is valid; Ql 3.3-4.7 No is not .
Both ranges must span the same number of indices.
Documents are renamed in the correct order to avoid collisions.
Source positions with no document are silently skipped.
Fails if any target index is occupied by a document not in the source range.
.It Bro Cm a | Cm activity Brc
Show an activity summary of indexed documents grouped by last-modified month.
Searches the current directory only.
.It Bro Cm ar | Cm activity-recursive Brc
Show an activity summary of indexed documents grouped by last-modified month.
Searches all subdirectories as well.
.It Cm R
Open the README.md (case-insensitive) document in the current working directory.
Creates README.md if it does not exist.
.It Cm C
Open the CLAUDE.md (case-insensitive) document in the current working directory.
Creates CLAUDE.md if it does not exist.
.It Cm t
Open the
.Pa nt_template
document in the current working directory.
Creates
.Pa nt_template.md
if it does not exist.
.It Cm util Cm month
Rename all files in the current directory whose names contain a spelled-out month name
(full or abbreviated, e.g.\&
.Dq January
or
.Dq Jan )
by replacing the month name with its two-digit numeric equivalent.
Word-boundary matching is used: the month name must not be adjacent to other letters.
.It Cm util Cm delim Ar D
Rename all nt-indexed files in the current directory so that the delimiter between the
numeric index and the title portion is
.Ar D
(e.g. replacing
.Ql _
with
.Ql - ) .
Files whose delimiter is already
.Ar D
are skipped.
.It Cm util Cm ext Ar E
Rename all nt-indexed files in the current directory so that their final extension is
.Ar E .
For example,
.Ql nt util ext md
converts
.Pa 001-example.txt
to
.Pa 001-example.md .
Files already using extension
.Ar E
are skipped.
.El
.Sh ENVIRONMENT
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Ev NT_EDITOR
Highest-priority editor override for
.Nm .
.It Ev VISUAL
Used when
.Ev NT_EDITOR
is not set.
Typically a GUI editor.
.It Ev EDITOR
Used when neither
.Ev NT_EDITOR
nor
.Ev VISUAL
is set.
Typically a terminal editor.
.Pp
If none of the above are set,
.Nm
falls back to
.Xr vim 1 .
.El
.Sh EXIT STATUS
The
.Nm
utility exits with one of the following values:
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It 0
Document, either new or existing, was successfully opened.
.It 1
Document, either new or existing, could not be opened.
.It >1
Another error occurred.
.El
.Sh EXAMPLES
The following examples show typical
.Nm
workflows, from simple to advanced.
.Ss Getting started
Create a first note in any directory:
.Pp
.Dl nt n
.Pp
This creates
.Pa 001.md
(or uses the template extension if one exists) and opens it in your editor.
Give the note a title:
.Pp
.Dl nt n meeting notes
.Pp
This creates
.Pa 002-meeting-notes.md
and opens it.
.Ss Navigating notes
Open the note you just created:
.Pp
.Dl nt l
.Pp
Open the second-to-last note:
.Pp
.Dl nt l 2
.Pp
Open a note by index:
.Pp
.Dl nt 1
.Pp
Open several notes at once:
.Pp
.Dl nt 1 3 5
.Ss Opening a range
Open notes 3 through 7:
.Pp
.Dl nt 3-7
.Pp
Hierarchical ranges are supported:
.Pp
.Dl nt 1.3-1.7
.Pp
Cross-depth ranges include all sub-indices within the bounds:
.Pp
.Dl nt 3-5.2
.Pp
Missing indices within the range are silently skipped.
.Ss Opening a subtree
Open all descendants under note 1:
.Pp
.Dl nt 1..
.Pp
Open only the immediate children of note 4:
.Pp
.Dl nt 4.
.Ss Creating sub-notes
Create a sub-note under note 4:
.Pp
.Dl nt n i 4.1 meeting follow-up
.Pp
This creates
.Pa 004.001-meeting-follow-up.md .
.Ss Copying from an existing note
Clone note 3 as a starting point for a new note:
.Pp
.Dl nt n c 3 revised draft
.Pp
Combine custom index and copy:
.Pp
.Dl nt n i 3.1 c 3 sub-variant
.Ss Renaming and renumbering
Rename note 5:
.Pp
.Dl nt r 5 project plan
.Pp
Rename the last note:
.Pp
.Dl nt rl brainstorm
.Pp
Reindex a single document to a new index (depth may change):
.Pp
.Dl nt ri 3 10
.Pp
Shift notes 3\(en5 so they start at 10 instead:
.Pp
.Dl nt ri 3-5 10-12
.Pp
Move a sub-range to a different parent:
.Pp
.Dl nt ri 1-3 3.5-3.7
.Ss Using a template
Create a template file (e.g.
.Pa nt_template.md )
in your notes directory.
All future notes created with
.Cm nt n
will start with that template's content.
The macros
.Cm %DATE
and
.Cm %TITLE
are expanded automatically.
.Ss Chaining commands
Hyphen-prefixed commands can be chained on a single line:
.Pp
.Dl nt -n standup notes -l -R
.Pp
This creates a new note titled
.Dq standup notes ,
opens the last note, and opens the README \(em all in one invocation.
A more involved chain:
.Pp
.Dl nt -n draft -r 2 revised title -5 -l
.Pp
This creates a note titled
.Dq draft ,
renames note 2, opens note 5, and opens the last note.
.Ss Checking activity
See which notes were modified recently:
.Pp
.Dl nt a
.Pp
Include subdirectories:
.Pp
.Dl nt ar
